    let mut player = Player {
        name: String::from(""),
        health: 0,
    };
    // Assume we have a method to set these fields
    player.set_name(String::from("Alice"));
    player.set_health(100);
    player
}

fn main() {
    let original_player = create_player();
    println!("Original player: {:?}", original_player);

    // Here is how you can clone the player using clone!
    let cloned_player = original_player.clone();

    println!("Cloned player (via clone!): {:?}", cloned_player);
}
```

When you call `create_player` to get a fresh instance of `Player`, you're borrowing a copy of the structure, which means each time you create a new `Player`, you end up with a different, independent instance of the same object. If you then call `original_player.clone()` on this newly created player, you'll obtain another completely independent instance of `Player`.

